[00:00.675] Passage 27. | 篇章27。
[00:02.765] Why does the idea of progress loom so large in the modern world? | 为什么进步的观念在现代世界中如此突出？
[00:07.455] Surely because progress of a particular kind is actually taking place around us and is becoming more and more manifest. | 当然是因为某种特定类型的进步正在我们身边发生，并且变得越来越明显。
[00:16.205] Although mankind has undergone no general improvement in intelligence or morality, it has made extraordinary progress in the accumulation of knowledge. | 尽管人类在智力或道德方面没有普遍进步，但在知识积累方面却取得了非凡的进展。
[00:26.375] Knowledge began to increase as soon as the thoughts of one individual could be communicated to another by means of speech. | 知识的增长始于个体思想可以通过言语传播给他人。
[00:34.695] With the invention of writing, a great advance was made, for knowledge could then be not only communicated but also stored. | 随着文字的发明，取得了巨大的进步，因为知识不仅可以传播，还可以储存。
[00:43.205] Libraries made education possible, and education in its turn added to libraries. | 图书馆使教育成为可能，而教育反过来又增加了图书馆的藏书。
[00:49.495] The growth of knowledge followed a kind of compound interest law, which was greatly enhanced by the invention of printing. | 知识的增长遵循一种复利法则，这通过印刷术的发明而大大增强。
[00:57.245] All this was comparatively slow until, with the coming of science, the tempo was suddenly raised. | 所有这一切都相对缓慢，直到科学的到来，节奏才突然加快。
[01:03.545] Then knowledge began to be accumulated according to a systematic plan. | 然后知识开始按照系统的计划积累。
[01:08.315] The trickle became a stream, the stream has now become a torrent. | 涓涓细流汇成小溪，小溪如今已成洪流。
[01:12.725] Moreover, as soon as new knowledge is acquired, it is now turned to practical account. | 此外，一旦获得新知识，它现在就被付诸实际应用。
[01:18.425] What is called modern civilization is not the result of a balanced development of all man's nature, but of accumulated knowledge applied to practical life. | 所谓的现代文明，并非人类所有本性均衡发展的结果，而是将累积的知识应用于实际生活。
[01:28.165] The problem now facing humanity is what is going to be done with all this knowledge. | 人类现在面临的问题是，所有这些知识将如何处理。
[01:34.885] As is so often pointed out, knowledge is a two-edged weapon, which can be used equally for good or evil. | 正如人们常指出的那样，知识是一把双刃剑，既可用于善，也可用于恶。
[01:41.565] It is now being used indifferently for both. | 它现在被不加区分地用于两者。
[01:45.025] Could any spectacle, for instance, be more grimly whimsical than that of gunners using science to shatter men's bodies, while close at hand, surgeons use it to restore them? | 例如，还有什么比炮兵利用科学摧毁人体，而近在咫尺的医生却用它来修复人体更令人毛骨悚然又异想天开的景象呢？
[01:55.935] We have to ask ourselves very seriously what will happen if this twofold use of knowledge with its ever-increasing power continues. | 我们必须非常认真地问自己，如果这种知识的双重用途及其日益增长的力量继续下去，将会发生什么。
